The problem report is then entered into System T, where it is compared with the Service Level Agreement (SLA) to determine if there are any discrepancies.

Next, the system determines the necessary countermeasures and assesses the significance of the issue for the customer. Based on this assessment, the measures are re-prioritized accordingly. A detailed problem report is then created and sent to the Service Management team.

The Service Management team investigates whether the problem can be analyzed. If it can be analyzed, the problem report is sent to the Resource Provisioning team. If it cannot be analyzed, the Service Management team proceeds to analyze the problem themselves.

In parallel, the Resource Provisioning team receives the detailed problem report and requests restoration if the issue can be resolved within two days. They track errors and undertake corrective actions as needed. Meanwhile, the Service Management team checks for possible problems and creates a trouble report or notification.

Once the Resource Provisioning team completes their corrective actions, they create a trouble-shooting report and send it back to the Service Management team. The Service Management team then sends this report to the Billing & Collections team if there is a need to report an SLA violation rebate.

The Service Management team also creates a trouble report and sends it to the customer if necessary. The customer receives the report and acknowledges it. If the issue is resolved, the process ends here.

If the issue is not resolved, the Service Management team continues to track errors and undertake further corrective actions. They create another trouble-shooting report and send it back to the Service Management team. This cycle continues until the issue is fully resolved.

Finally, the Service Management team creates a customer report and sends it to the customer, marking the end of the process.

If minor corrective actions are taken, a problem resolution report is created and sent to Customer Service.

In parallel, if automatic resource restoration is required, a request is created and sent to Resource Provisioning. Resource Provisioning tracks errors and undertakes necessary corrective actions. They then create a troubleshooting report, which is sent back to Service Management. Service Management uses this report to create a final problem resolution report.

Customer Service then prepares a performance report based on the service provided. If there is an SLA violation, a rebate report is sent to Billing & Collections. Finally, a report is sent to the customer, concluding the process.

Throughout the process, there are checks and balances to ensure that the problem is addressed efficiently and effectively, with special attention given to premium customers. The process ends when all necessary reports are completed and sent to the relevant parties.
